# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Misconceptions
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------

oakcurric:misconception-artists-hold-drawing-tool-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists have to hold a drawing tool with their hands to make marks."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can make marks by holding a drawing tool but
  they can also make marks without directly touching the drawing tool."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.086271Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-backgrounds-artworks-important-images-within
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Backgrounds in artworks are not as important as the images within an
  artwork."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that backgrounds to artworks can make an image more
  interesting, or tell us more about the images within an artwork. They can also make an
  artwork look more three-dimensional."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.092573Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-spread-images-individually-across
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students spread images individually out across the page without making visual
  connections."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage students to use overlapping and layering with their images to
  create interest and visual connections."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.094474Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-make-artwork-images
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists only make artwork with images."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that artists can make artwork with images, but they can also
  create artwork with words."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.095721Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-petals-flower-flat
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The petals of a flower are flat."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that the petals of a flower curve and bend, so are not flat
  shapes. They are a three-dimensional form."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.097411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-africa-one-country
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Africa is one country."@en ;
  curric:correction """Africa is a continent made up of many different countries and cultures, past
  and present. Different maps from different times can show this."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.098070Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-press-hard-engrave-design
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You need to press down hard to engrave a design."@en ;
  curric:correction """Children should be encouraged not to press too hard when engraving their
  design to avoid making holes in the matrix."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.099496Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-part-triptych-separate-unconnected
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That each part of a triptych is separate and unconnected."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that in a triptych, each panel shares ideas with the others
  to create one single artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101761Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-match-colours-first-attempt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists can always match colours on the first attempt."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that it can take an artist several tries to make the correct
  colour. By practicing colour mixing, artists can improve over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101800Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-joining-methods-equally-strong
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All joining methods are equally strong."@en ;
  curric:correction "Some methods, like a tight twist are much stronger than others."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-maps-look-like-ones-phones
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All maps have to look like the ones on phones or paper."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that some artists make maps with patterns, colours and
  memories."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.101829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-silhouettes-made-black-card-paper
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Silhouettes must be made of black card or paper."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that silhouettes are often made of black paper or card as
  this shows up well against a light background, but it is up to the artist which solid
  colour they will use to make their silhouette."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.103037Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-artwork-finished-artists-change
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once an artwork is finished, artists should never change or improve it."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that looking at your work and finding ways you could improve
  it is an important part of being an artist."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.105847Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-use-paintbrushes-apply-paint
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists only use paintbrushes to apply paint."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists can use a paintbrush to apply paint, but they can also use other
  tools, such as leaves, sticks and pinecones."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.106087Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-patterns-made-shapes-lines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Patterns can only be made with shapes and lines."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that shapes and lines can be used to make patterns, but
  motifs can be used to create more complex patterns."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.110887Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-feel-same-colour
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We all feel the same about every colour."@en ;
  curric:correction "Remind pupils that everyone feels colours differently."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.111531Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-use-much-clay-earth-want
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "We can use as much clay from the Earth as we want!"@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that we share natural resources and use them carefully, so
  there is enough for everyone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.113399Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-marbling-prints-made-one-way
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Marbling prints can only be made in one way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Marbling can be made in lots of different ways, such as ink or chalk floating
  on water. Marbling can also be made with shaving foam."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114455Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-draw-things-exactly-look
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists always draw things exactly how they look in real life."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists sometimes draw things as they look in real life but can also draw
  things from their imagination."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.114471Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-use-scissors-cut
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Some pupils may think they can only use scissors to cut paper."@en ;
  curric:correction """Model tearing and cutting and explain to pupils that choice between the two
  is important. Tearing makes soft textures like grass or clouds. Cutting makes sharp edges
  for shapes like windows. Think about which works best for your design."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115241Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-men-important-history-trade
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Only men were important in history and trade."@en ;
  curric:correction """Women played key roles such as making silk, running markets and sharing
  stories. Artists invite us to think about this through their work."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.115511Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-abstract-symbols-need-explained-others
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All abstract symbols need to be explained to others."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that some abstract symbols hold personal or cultural meanings
  that don’t have to be explained. The West African Adinkra symbol Sankofa, literally means
  “go back and fetch it” and suggests that we carry our past with us."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.118248Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-evaluating-saying-like-dislike
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Evaluating is only saying what you like or dislike"@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that evaluation is more than just saying what we like or
  dislike about an artwork. It should help an artist improve their work over time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.126444Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-press-hard-using-charcoal
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You need to press down hard when using charcoal."@en ;
  curric:correction """Pressing down too hard will break the charcoal. You need to be much more
  gentle."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.126453Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-primary-colors-made-mixing-other
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Primary colors are made by mixing other colours together."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that primary colours cannot be created by mixing other
  colours. Secondary colours are made by mixing two primary colours together. For example,
  blue and yellow make green."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.128240Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-need-special-expensive-things-make
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You need special or expensive things to make fabric patterns."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that you can use natural objects, paper and wax to make
  patterns on fabric. You can use simple, safe materials to tell powerful stories through
  cloth."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.128275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-rush-drawing-without-observing
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may rush through the drawing without observing carefully, believing
  that drawing quickly means drawing well."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Children could be reminded to take their time and look closely at the
  subject."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.128393Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-make-artwork-themselves
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists always make artwork by themselves."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can choose to work by themselves, but they can
  also plan and make work collaboratively."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.130019Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-looms-rectangular
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All looms are rectangular."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that some weavings are made on square or rectangular looms,
  but weavings do not have to be made on looms with straight sides. Looms can be curved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.130114Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-texture-shown-drawing-painting
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Texture can only be shown with drawing or painting"@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that artists might choose to use clay to represent textures as
  it can show a wide range of different surfaces."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131045Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-texture-describes-something-rough-bumpy
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Texture describes something rough, bumpy or hard to touch."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind students that textures can be rough, hard and bumpy but they can also
  be smooth, soft and fuzzy."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.131581Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-marbling-invented-britain
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Marbling was invented in Britain."@en ;
  curric:correction """Art historians are not exactly sure where marbling was invented, but it was
  certainly popular in places such as Japan a long time before it was brought to Britain."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.132818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-take-photograph-front
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "You always have to take a photograph from the front."@en ;
  curric:correction """You can experiment with angles and frames to make your photographs more
  interesting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133102Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paintbrushes-left-dirty-used-again
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Paintbrushes can be left dirty and used again without cleaning."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that paintbrushes like to be cleaned and left on top of water
  pots so the next artist can use them."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133335Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-think-buildings-same-dont
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may think that all buildings are the same and don’t understand why
  some materials are better for the environment."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Some buildings waste energy, while others are designed to protect nature."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.133572Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artwork-permanent
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "That all artwork is permanent."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that some artwork can be made to be permanent, but other
  artwork can be made to only last a short time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.135253Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-depict-texture-water-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists will always depict the texture of water in the same way."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that although water itself always feels wet and smooth,
  artists might use their materials to show the water being bubbly, smooth or rough. Artists
  can describe this as the texture of the water."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.137345Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-paint-mixed-paint-palette
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Paint can only be mixed in a paint palette."@en ;
  curric:correction """Paint can be mixed in a paint palette, but it can also be mixed on paper to
  create a blend."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139895Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-one-spiky-texture-hedgehog
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "There is only one spiky texture on a hedgehog."@en ;
  curric:correction "A hedgehog has a spiky texture, but also has soft, furry ears."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.139903Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-architectural-designs-symmetrical
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All architectural designs are symmetrical."@en ;
  curric:correction "Some buildings are also asymmetrical."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.140492Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-art-copying-see
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that art is only about copying what you see, not what you
  feel or imagine."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Art can involve expressive mark-making, imaginative thinking and
  communicating mood or ideas."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.141311Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-hold-camera-device-landscape
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may hold the camera or device in a landscape grip instead of
  portrait."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Pupils should hold their device/camera with a portrait grip."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.141405Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-shape-make-strong-building
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Any shape can make a strong building."@en ;
  curric:correction "Architects select specific shapes and structures to make homes stable."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.141411Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-textiles-fabric
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All textiles are fabric."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that fabric is one kind of textile. There are many different
  kinds of textiles including felted materials, waterproof materials and synthetic fibers."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142295Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-spread-their-images-separately
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may spread their images separately across the page without using
  layering."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Layering is used in collage to create further meaning and depth to the
  artwork."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142731Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-profile-portrait-eyes
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might think that, in a profile portrait, both eyes and ears are
  visible."""@en ;
  curric:correction """In a true profile portrait, only one eye and one ear are typically visible,
  as the subject is viewed from the side."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.142737Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-art-materials-bought-rather-made
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Art materials must be bought rather than made."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can buy their ink from a shop, but they can also
  make their own from natural materials."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143342Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-artists-depict-water-using-colour
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Artists always depict water using the colour blue."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can use blue to represent water, but they can
  use lots of other colours as well."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143551Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-drawings-look-exactly-like-object
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Drawings always have to look exactly like the object the artist is
  observing."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Drawing exercises focus more on artists using their eyes to carefully observe
  lines and shapes, rather than trying to create a drawing that looks exactly like the
  object."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143740Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-straight-lines-rather-curved-lines
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Straight lines rather than curved lines are used to draw a sphere."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that if straight lines are used, the sphere can look flat
  even though the artist has used tone. Curved lines help the moon to look spherical."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143889Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-once-design-created-cannot-adapted
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Once  a design has been created, it cannot be adapted or changed."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can change their ideas as they go, making
  changes to their design as they continue through the design and making process."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143897Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-looms-cannot-made-everyday-objects
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Looms cannot be made from everyday objects."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that looms can be made on a wide variety of frames, including
  found sticks or paper plates."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.143905Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-opinions-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "All opinions should be the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that other people might disagree with you or have a different
  opinion. This is what helps to make art exciting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.144112Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-tone-achieved-pressure
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Tone is always achieved through pressure."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that tone can be achieved through adding pressure, but layers
  of material can also be built up or removed to vary tone."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.144654Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-chalk-pastels-come-black-white
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Chalk pastels only come in black and white."@en ;
  curric:correction """Chalk pastels come in black and white, but they also come in a wide range of
  bright and vibrant colours."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.146812Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-mark-shape-needs-identical-placed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Every mark or shape needs to be identical and placed in a perfectly regular
  sequence to make a pattern."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that patterns do not always have to be exactly the same each
  time, but they still follow a rule or idea."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.146818Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-emotions-shown-images-mark-making
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Emotions can be shown through images but not through mark-making."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that different styles of marks can show the emotions of the
  artist, such as rounded lines showing that an artist might be feeling happy and calm. The
  artist does not need to create an image to express an emotion."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.146823Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-warp-weft-threads-same
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Warp and weft threads are the same."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that the warp threads hold the weft threads in place. These
  are the first threads attached to the loom."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.146829Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-portrait-means-picture-persons-face
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """That portrait means the picture is always a person's face, and landscape means
  it can only be a big outdoor scene."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that portrait just means the paper is taller than it is wide,
  and landscape means it’s wider than tall. You can use both for many different kinds of
  pictures, not just faces or outdoor scenes."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.147122Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-hot-cold-colours-change-temperature
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Hot or cold colours can change the temperature."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that these colours do not really change the temperature, but
  they can make people feel warmer by looking at them, as they remind them of hot things
  like the sun or a fire."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.149715Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-eyes-drawn-towards
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that the eyes are drawn towards the top of the face."@en ;
  curric:correction "The eyes are halfway between the top of the head and the chin."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.152207Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-assume-maps-accurate-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils might assume that maps always have to be accurate like road maps or
  atlases."""@en ;
  curric:correction "Artists can creative in the way they express their ideas or experiences."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.152213Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-once-base-painted
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may think that once the base is painted the 3D artwork is
  completed."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists often reflect and revisit their work to add further detail and bring
  their artwork to life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.155730Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-feel-need-cut-clay
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may feel the need to cut the clay straight away before connecting the
  dots."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Encourage pupils to connect the dots carefully first before cutting. Consider
  giving them a light pencil or tool to trace the outline before cutting."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.157431Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-drawing-artists-use-their-hands
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "When drawing, artists only use their hands."@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that artists can use their whole body when creating
  marks."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.158515Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-everyone-group-same-ideas
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Everyone in the group has to have the same ideas."@en ;
  curric:correction """It's okay to have different ideas as good teams listen, share, and find ways
  to combine or choose ideas together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162002Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-children-think-maps-show-real
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Children may think that maps show only real places, exactly as they are in
  real life."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists create expressive maps from their memory and imagination that may not
  look like real life."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.162629Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-cant-move-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that they can't move away from their initial plan."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists change their artwork as they go by responding to reflection and
  feedback."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.163673Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-scissors-held-thumb-bottom-index
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Scissors should be held with the thumb on the bottom, and the index finger on
  the top."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind children that scissors should be used with the thumb on top, nearest
  to the ceiling. Scissors should also be held in the same position, cutting away from the
  body with the paper being moved."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164094Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-press-lightly-result-their
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may press too lightly and as a result their marks will not be
  clear."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Give plenty of oportunity to create drafts of their monoprint, improving the
  line quality each time."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.164526Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-paint-fox-background-similar
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Pupils may paint the fox and background in similar colours, making the
  sculpture blend in."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Remind pupils that the fox should stand out - encourage warm, bright colours
  for the fox against darker shades in the background."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165275Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-consider-materials-joined-together
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Students may not consider how materials are joined together."@en ;
  curric:correction """When constructing a structure, we must think carefully about how they are
  joined together."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165499Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-art-still-doesnt
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Pupils may think that all art is still and that it doesn't show movement."@en ;
  curric:correction """Artists have lots of ways to show change or movement such as using lines,
  colours, and even how they arrange things in the picture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.165787Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-symbols-detailed
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "Symbols have to be detailed."@en ;
  curric:correction "Symbols can be refined and made simple."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168288Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-pupils-think-one-layer-papier
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The pupils may think that one layer of papier-mâché is enough."@en ;
  curric:correction """We need multiple layers to make it strong. Artists build layer by layer to
  shape and secure their sculpture."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168378Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-painting-pupils-try-paint-everything
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """When painting, pupils may try to paint everything at once without letting
  layers dry."""@en ;
  curric:correction """When painting, it is important to paint the background first and let it dry
  before adding other elements on top."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168429Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-art-copying-things-look-like
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Art is only about copying what things look like, rather than expressing
  feelings."""@en ;
  curric:correction "You can use colours, shapes, or lines to share your mood or ideas."@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.168445Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-clay-use-better-balanced-your
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement "The more clay you use, the better balanced your figure will be."@en ;
  curric:correction """Using more clay does not always make your figure balanced. A figure is
  balanced when the weight is spread out evenly."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.169617Z"^^xsd:dateTime .

oakcurric:misconception-students-attempt-create-piece-resembles
  a curric:Misconception ;
  curric:statement """Students may attempt to create a piece that resembles a two-dimensional image
  as a result of not layering the materials."""@en ;
  curric:correction """Students should be reminded to layer materials to create a three-dimensional
  piece."""@en ;
  dcterms:modified "2026-06-07T15:30:15.170635Z"^^xsd:dateTime .
